  "markdown": "Contents Menu Expand Light mode Dark mode Auto light/dark, in light mode Auto light/dark, in dark mode [Skip to content](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html#furo-main-content)\n[BlueQubit Python SDK 0.18.8b1 documentation](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html)\n[ ![Light Logo](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/_static/logo_black.svg) ![Dark Logo](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/_static/logo.svg) BlueQubit Python SDK 0.18.8b1 ](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html)\n  * [Quick Start](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html)\n  * [API Reference](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/bluequbit.sdk.html)\n  * [License](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/LICENSE.html)\n\n\n[ Back to top ](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html)\n# Quick Start[\u00b6](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html#quick-start \"Link to this heading\")\nBlueQubit Python SDK is a quantum computing SDK that lets you build, optimize, and run quantum circuits on BlueQubit platform from Python. Whether you need quantum simulation on large CPU/GPU devices or quantum circuit optimization at scale, this quantum development kit has you covered.\n  1. Register on <https://app.bluequbit.io> and copy the API token.\n  2. Install the quantum computing Python package from PyPI:\n\n\n\n```\npip install bluequbit\n\n```\n\n  1. Import and initialize the quantum Python SDK (importing also Qiskit for circuit building):\n\n\n\n```\nimport qiskit\n\nimport bluequbit\n\nbq_client = bluequbit.init(\"<token>\")\n\n```\n\n  1. Quick example of how to run a quantum circuit using the quantum SDK:\n\n\n\n```\nqc_qiskit = qiskit.QuantumCircuit(2)\nqc_qiskit.h(0)\nqc_qiskit.x(1)\n\njob_result = bq_client.run(qc_qiskit, job_name=\"testing_1\")\n\nstate_vector = job_result.get_statevector()\n# returns a NumPy array of [0. +0.j 0. +0.j 0.70710677+0.j 0.70710677+0.j]\n\n```\n\n## More Examples[\u00b6](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html#more-examples \"Link to this heading\")\n  1. Here is an example to run the previous code asynchronously:\n\n\n\n```\n# This line is non-blocking.\njob = bq_client.run(qc_qiskit, job_name=\"testing_1\", asynchronous=True)\n\n# This line blocks until the job is completed.\njob_result = bq_client.wait(job.job_id)\n\n# If you want to cancel a pending job.\nbq_client.cancel(job.job_id)\n\n```\n\n  1. This is how you can use our mps.cpu device for quantum simulation:\n\n\n\n```\n# a 40 qubit GHZ state\nnum_qubits = 40\nqc = qiskit.QuantumCircuit(num_qubits)\nqc.h(0)\nfor i in range(num_qubits - 1):\n     qc.cx(i, i+1)\n\nqc.measure_all()\n\noptions = {\n    \"mps_bond_dimension\": 2,\n}\nresult = bq_client.run(qc, device=\"mps.cpu\", options=options) # should take ~30seconds\nprint(result.get_counts())\n\n```\n\nThe mps.gpu device can be used in the same way for accelerated quantum simulation. Note that while mps.gpu is faster, you need to have a certain amount of minimal balance to be able to use it.\n  1. To run our Pauli Path simulation for computing observable expectations:\n\n\n\n```\n# Only Qiskit Circuits are supported\nqc = qiskit.QuantumCircuit(3)\nqc.h(0)\nqc.h(1)\nqc.h(2)\nqc.ry(0.3, 0)\nqc.rz(0.6, 1)\nqc.rx(0.7, 2)\n\npauli_sum = [\n    (\"XYZ\", 0.5),\n    (\"XXX\", 0.2),\n    (\"XII\", 0.3),\n    (\"III\", 0.4),\n]\n\noptions = {\n    \"pauli_path_truncation_threshold\": 0.1,\n}\nresult = bq_client.run(qc, device=\"pauli-path\", pauli_sum=pauli_sum, options=options)\nprint(result.expectation_value)\n# compare with \"mps.cpu\"\nresult_mps = bq_client.run(qc, device=\"mps.cpu\", pauli_sum=pauli_sum)\nprint(result_mps.expectation_value) # exact\n\n```\n\n  1. An example of how to run a Pennylane circuit using the SDK:\n\n\n\n```\nimport pennylane as qml\nfrom pennylane import numpy as np\n\n# use \"bluequbit.cpu\" device name to run on CPU\ndev = qml.device(\"bluequbit.cpu\", wires=1, token=\"<token>\")\n# use \"bluequbit.gpu\" device name to run on GPU\n# dev = qml.device(\"bluequbit.gpu\", wires=1, token=\"<token>\")\n\n@qml.qnode(dev)\ndef circuit(angle):\n    qml.RY(angle, wires=0)\n    return qml.probs(wires=0)\n\n\nprobabilities = circuit(np.pi / 4)\n# returns a NumPy array of [0.85355339 0.14644661]\n\n```\n\nTo use the Pennylane plugin, you must have `pennylane` version **0.39 or above** installed. `bluequbit.cpu` supports Pennylane circuits with up to **32 qubits** (wires). `bluequbit.gpu` supports Pennylane circuits with up to **33 qubits** (wires).\n  1. This SDK requires Python versions 3.10 or above. The package is tested extensively on Python 3.10.\n\n\n## Questions and Issues[\u00b6](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html#questions-and-issues \"Link to this heading\")\nPlease submit questions and issues to info@bluequbit.io.\n[ Next API Reference ](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/bluequbit.sdk.html)\nCopyright \u00a9 2026, BlueQubit \nMade with [Sphinx](https://www.sphinx-doc.org/) and [@pradyunsg](https://pradyunsg.me)'s [Furo](https://github.com/pradyunsg/furo)\nLast updated on True\nOn this page \n  * [Quick Start](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html)\n    * [More Examples](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html#more-examples)\n    * [Questions and Issues](https://app.bluequbit.io/sdk-docs/index.html#questions-and-issues)\n\n\n",
